df.head()

df.shape

df.describe()

df['species']=iris.target

df.columns

'''# descriptive statistics we r going to do here

print("mean :",df.mean(numeric_only=True))

# std deviation - it will spread the data with ref to mean
Measures how spread out data values are from the mean
Low SD → values are close to the mean
High SD → values are widely spread
Shows data variability
Used to understand consistency of data

# skewness - it explains abt the the (asymmetry),left(data is left to mean),right(data is right to mean), if data is in middle(skewness is "0".. it means equally divided)
Measures asymmetry of data distribution
Skewness = 0 → perfectly symmetric
Positive skew → tail on the right
Negative skew → tail on the left
Shows data bias direction


# kurtosis - it tells abt peakness used to identify outliers (like normal deviation)
 Measures peakedness or tail heaviness
High kurtosis → sharp peak, heavy tails
Low kurtosis → flat peak, light tails
Normal distribution kurtosis ≈ 3
Indicates outliers presence'''

print("median :" , df.median(numeric_only=True))

print("dt_deviation :", df.std(numeric_only=True))

print("kurtosis :" , df.kurtosis(numeric_only=True))

print("skewness :", df.skew(numeric_only=True))

